<TITLE> Huji activists get 20 years for holding grenades </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 15 (bdnews24.com)  A Satkhira court on Sunday sentenced leading activist of militant group Harkat-ul-Jihad (Huji), Abu Jandal, and an accomplice Nazrul Ghorami, to 20 years rigorous imprisonment each, for possession of a large cache of powerful hand grenades. Judge Ashish Ranjan Das, of Special Judge's Court-1, also fined them Tk 20,000 or another year in prison in case of failure to pay the sum. The Rapid Action Battalion recovered 41 grenades from the house of Ghorami, in Satkhira, based on a confessional statement of Jandal. RAB had arrested the leading Huji militant, mufti Moinuddin Sheikh alias Abu Jandal, on Feb 14 for alleged links to the Aug 21, 2004, grenade attack on an Awami League rally. The elite security force filed a case under the explosives act with Debhata Police Station against Jandal and Ghorami on Feb 16. Debhata police chief Lokman Hekim pressed charges against the two on Mar 17. Some 15 witnesses were deposed in the trial, bdnews24.c
